OUR VEHICLE STARTED UNLOADING INTO THE WRONG TANK (THERE ARE 2 TANKS AT THE DELIVERY LOCATION), WHICH OVERFILLED, CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL. DUE TO HEAVY RAINS, SOME PRODUCT RAN INTO THE CITY STORM DRAIN, AND WAS ROUTED THROUGH THE CITY'S FILTRATION SYSTEM, AVOIDING RELEASE INTO A WATERWAY. THE BALANCE WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL, CAUSING NO APPARENT ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO MARY ANN SYKES WITH THE VA STATE WATER CONTROL BOARD ON 1-9-90.

PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED OFF AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE BERGEN COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY ENVIROMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES, INC (NEWBURGH BRANCH). DISPOSAL OF WASTE WILL ALSO BE HANDLED BY THEM. INCIDENT REPORTED TO NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, REPORT NUMBER 00323. ALSO REPORTED TO NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION (REPORT NUMBER 9001040025). ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: MORE FREQUENT INSPECTIONS OF HOSE, AND FITTINGS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0915 HOURS, 1-11-90, CAR WAS SWITCHED INTO YARD TRACK AND AT TIME OF COUPLING INTO OTHER CARS, PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF VENT ASSEMBLY ON TOP OF CAR AND ONTO GROUND. EMPLOYEE STANDING NEAR IMPACT WAS EXPOSED TO THE FUMES OF THE VAPOR. NO TIME LOST OR MEDICAL TREATMENT WAS REQUIRED. OLIN CHEMICAL SENT CREW TO MAKE REPAIRS AND FOUND THE VENT ASSEMBLY WAS DISLODGED ON TOP OF CAR. REPAIRS COMPLETED AT 1545 SAME DAY. SODA ASH WAS SPREAD ON THE AREA TO NEUTRALIZE PRODUCT. ALL APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.
IN THE COURSE OF LOADING, A FIRE AND EXPLOSION OCCURED IN OUR TRAILER. WE BELIEVE THAT ALL THE MATERIAL THAT WAS LOADED ON THE TRAILER WAS BURNED UP.

OUR UNIT WAS ON THE LOADING RACK AT PENNWALT CORP. AT GREENS BAYOU, TX. AND HAD BEEN LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS WHEN THIOPHENE STARTED LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE AROUND THE TRAILER DISCHARGE LINE, CONNECTING TO THE TRAILER. ALSO THE VACUUM BREAKER VALVE WAS LEAKING AT THE DOME AREA.

column168: DRIVER HAD A SPLIT DELIVERY BETWEEN CUMBERLAND FARMS STORE #2810 AND #2831. BOTH STORES ARE IN MANCHESTER, NH. DRIVER THOUGHT HE WAS AT STORE #2810 WHICH HAS 8000 GALLON INGROUND TANKS. THE DRIVER, HOWEVER, WAS AT STORE #2831, WHICH ONLY HAS 4000 GALLON IN GROUND TANKS. THE DRIVER UNLOADED 780 GALLONS OF SUPER NO-LEAD WHEN THE TANK OVERFLOWED CAUSING THE 4" ELBOW ATTACHED TO THE HOSE TO LEAK THE CONTENTS OF THE HOSE ONTO THE GROUND. APPROX 40 GALS OF SUPER NO-LEAD SPILLED. THE MANCHESTER, NH FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED AND ASSISTED IN THE CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL. CLEAN HARBORS WAS CALLED AND CLEANED UP AND REMOVED THE SAND AND GRAVEL USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. SOME OF THE GASOLINE. SOME OF THE GASOLINE GOT INTO A MANHOLE COVER BUT COLLECTED IN THE CATCH BASIN. THE GASOLINE DID NOT ENTER THE WATERWAYS. THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED WITH SPILL RAGS.

DOCKWORKER NOTICED MOISTURE ON ONE CARTON AND FOUND ONE INNER CONTAINER WHOSE SIDE SEAM WAS APPARENTLY DEFECTIVE. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED PLACING THE PACKAGE INSIDE A STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.

FREIGHT WAS PUNCTURED BY A F/1. ABOUT FIVE GALLONS LEAKED OUT INTO THE TRAILER BEFORE THE FREIGHT WAS RECOUPED INTO A PLASTIC OVERPACK CONTAINER. ACID NEUTRALIZER WAS USED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. PROTECTIVE GEAR WAS USED BY THE PEOPLE INVOLVED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES NOR DOES IT APPEAR THAT ANY OF THE FREIGHT WAS DAMAGED. column168: PRE-INCIDENT:     TRAILER WAS BACKED UP UNDER AN ELEVATED STORAGE TANK FOR LOADING. A RUBBER HOSE FROM THE TANK WAS PLACED IN THE TOP OF THE TANKER AND THE VALVE ON THE TANK WAS OPENED.       INCIDENT:     IT APPEARS THAT THE DISCHARGE LINE ON THE REAR OF THE TANKER WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED. DURING THE LOADING OF MATERIAL INTO THE TOP OF THE TANKER, IT APPEARS THAT HYDROSTATIC PRESSURE POPPED OFF THE SAFETY CAP ON THIS LINE, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL.       RESPONSE:     THE VALVE WAS SHUT, SODA ASH WAS IMMEDIATELY APPLIED TO NEUTRALIZE AND STABILIZE THE MATERIAL. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRATOR ARRIVED ON SITE TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES, INCLUDING REMOVAL OF THE STABILIZED MATERIAL AND ANY VISIBLY CONTAMINATED SOILS. THIS MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATIONS, AT A PERMITTED FACILITY.

INSPECTION OF UNIT EN ROUTE TO CONSIGNEE FOUND SLIGHT DRIPPING OF PRODUCT THROUGH BOTTOM OF TRAILER THROUGH INSULATION AND OUTER SKIN. DRIPPING CONTAINED IN BUCKET. RESPONSE TEAM FROM MATLACK INC. THE INTERNAL VALVE DIDN'T CLOSE PROPERLY. THIS ALLOWED MATERIAL TO BE TRAPPED BETWEEN THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVE. WHEN THE DRIVER TOOK THE CAP OFF, HE LOST ABOUT 2 GALLONS.

RAILCAR STILL HAD PRODUCT IN IT FROM PREVIOUS LOAD. COULD NOT SEE HEEL THAT WAS STUCK TO THE ENDS OF THE TANK CAR. RAILCAR WAS DESIGNED FOR 201000 LB PAYLOAD AND OVERFILLED AT 187000 LB. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY REPORTED SPILL, MADE AREA WAS SECURE AND RETURNED BALANCE OF PRODUCT TO SHIPPER. AFTER HIS DEPARTURE, SPILL SITE CLEAN UP PROCEDURES INITIATED. SPILL SITE HAS UNDERGONE TOTAL CLEAN UP AS OF JANUARY 23, 1990.

column168: DURING SWITCHING, GATX 40569 WAS DISCOVERED WITH WETNESS DOWN ITS SIDE; CAR MOVEMENT WAS STOPPED AND INSPECTED BY SOO LINE PERSONNEL.  THE CAUSE WAS DETERMINED TO BE LOOSE BOLTS AROUND MANWAY COVER PLATE. BOLTS AROUND MANWAY COVER PLATE WERE TIGHTENED AND CAR WAS ALLOWED TO MOVE FORWARD TO DESTINATION.

DURING DELIVERY OPERATIONS A SMALL PACKAGE WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT AT THE LAST RECIPIENT'S LOCATION, AND THE PACKAGE WAS BLOWN ONTO A PUBLIC ROAD WHERE IT WAS CRUSHED BY SEVERAL VEHICLES. THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN TWO GLASS VIALS SURROUNDED BY ABSORBENT MATERIAL INSIDE LEAD PIGS, WHICH WERE INSIDE SEPARATE PLASTIC CONTAINERS LOCATED IN A STYROFOAM BLOCK WITHIN AN OUTSIDE FIBERBOARD BOX. ONE VIAL WAS RECOVERED INTACT. THE OTHER VIAL CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 2 MCI IN-111 WAS TOTALLY CRUSHED ON THE ROADWAY AND THE CONTENTS HAD BEEN DISSIPATED IN THE SNOW. A HEALTH PHYSICIST FROM THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC HEALTH INVESTIGATED THE INCIDENT AT THE SCENE AND DETERMINED THAT ANY RESULTING CONTAMINATION FROM THE SHORTLIVED ISOTOPE WOULD NOT REPRESENT ANY RISK TO THE PUBLIC, AND HE DID NOT REQUIRE ANY ADDITIONAL ACTION TO BE TAKEN.
column172: General packaging, for type A radioactive materials

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING TWO PRODUCTS, DIESEL FUEL AND UNLEADED GASOLINE. HE HAD BEEN WARNED OF A POSSIBLE DEFECTIVE UNLEADED METER SET STOP. HE SET THE DIESEL FUEL METER PRESET AND BEGAN LOADING. HE THEN STARTED THE UNLEADED GASOLINE METER, STANDING BY IT TO REACT TO ANY POSSIBLE MALFUNCTION. WHILE ATTENDING TO THE UNLEADED METER, THE DIESEL FUEL METER OVERRAN THE PRESET SHUTOFF, OVERFILLING THE CARGO TANK AND SPILLING DIESEL FUEL ONTO THE LOAD RACK. OUR DRIVER THEN HALTED ALL LOADING, AND FLUSHED THE RACK CONTAINMENT AREA WITH WATER INTO THE RACK DRAINAGE SYSTEM, WHICH LEADS TO AN OIL/WATER SEPARATOR, WHERE THE DIESEL WATER MIXTURE IS SEPARATED AND REPROCESSED. OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED CHEVRON USA OFFICIALS OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE METERS AS OUTLINED IN THEIR RACK PROCEDURES. NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ESCAPED THE RACK CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO OUR MARTINEZ FACILITY AND CLEANED.

ETCX 30000 DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND INSTALLED LIQUID LINE NOZZLE FLANGE GASKET. CAR MOVED TO CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING.
DRIVER ERROR DURING PUMPING OFF SHIPMENT INTO STORAGE RESULTED IN STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWING. MATERIAL CONTAINED WITHIN THE DIKED AREA AND CLEAN-UP BY RECEIVING PERSONNEL.

DRIVER TOOK STICK READING IN TANK BEFORE BEGINNING TO DROP. ACCORDING TO 10,000 GALLON, 96 INCH TANK CHART, 38 INCHES REPRESENT 3674 GALLONS.HE WAS GOING TO DROP 6000 GALLONS. THE TANK FILLED UP BEFORE THE ENTIRE 6000 WAS DROPPED. HE DISCONNECTED HOSE TO TRY AND DROP BALANCE IN #2 DIESEL STORAGE. PRODUCT IN HOSE SPILLED ONTO GROUND AND FLOWED INTO CATCH BASIN ON STATION PROPERTY. CATCH BASIN DRAINED INTO CREEK NORTH OF STATION. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL WAS NOTIFIED TO DO CLEAN UP. DNR NOTIFIED.

column168: DRUMS WERE IN NOSE OF TRAILER. LOAD BAR WAS ACROSS TRAILER HOLDING DRUMS IN PLACE. PALLET JACK AND A SKID OF STEEL SHEETING WERE AGAINST LOAD BAR. THE SKID OF STEEL SHEETING SLID, BENDING THE LOAD BAR AND PUNCTURED 2 DRUMS. OIL DRY WAS APPLIED TO THE LIQUID INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ALSO ON THE DRIVEWAY AND STREET WAS WASHED DOWN THE STORM DRAIN, BY THE FIRE DEPT UNDER AUTHORIZATION OF THE CAMDEN COUNTY DEPT OF HEALTH REP VINCE BARBEB. THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUMS AND RETURNED TO THE PHILADELPHIA TERMINAL. THE DRUMS HAVE BEEN RETURNED TO SANDOZ CHEMICAL IN MT. HOLLY, NC AND THE CONTAMINATED OIL DRY HAS BEEN DISPOSED OF AS DIRECTED BY THE DEPT. OF HEALTH OFFICER.

AT 4:13 PM ON JANUARY 7, 1990 DIVISION OPERATIONS CENTER WAS NOTIFIED GAPX 5031 CONTAINING METHYL-TERT-BUTYL ETHER WAS LEAKING AT DUMAS, TEXAS ON BOISE CITY SUB DIVISION. THIS CAR MOVED FROM AMARILLO ON TR. 1534-05 AND SET OUT AT DUMAS FOR FURTHER HANDLING BY LKT221-08 TO DIAMOND SHAMROCK AT MACHOVEC, TEXAS. MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT AMARILLO ARRIVED AT 6:25 PM AND FOUND LOOSE PLUG IN LIQUID UNLOADING LINE ON TOP OF CAR CAUSED BY HIGH PRESSURE. TIGHTENED TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. LEAK WAS CONTAINED AT 7:15 PM. DUMAS POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED 3 BY 6 BLOCK AREA AND GAS AND ELECTRICAL FACILITIES CUT OFF AT SEVERAL LOCATIONS. AT ABOUT 7:15 PM CITIZENS WERE ALLOWED TO ENTER HOMES AND EVACUATED AREA.
DAN MURPHY WAS LOADING THE SKID ON TRAILER 15-6638 (PON) AND SPEARED THE PAIL WITH HIS TOW-MOTOR. THE SPILL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.

DURING UNLOADING, DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE SKID WHICH HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. ONE PAIL WHICH HAD CRACKED WHERE THE LID IS FASTENED TO THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INSIDE RECOVERY PAIL AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED.

A DOCK WORKER REPORTS THAT HE HAD DROPPED A CARTON OF POISON B. THE OPERATIONS MANAGER INSPECTED THE CARTON AND NOTICED IT BECOMING MOIST ON THE BOTTOM SO HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM. NO LEAKAGE OCCURRED OUTSIDE THE RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WAS IMMEDIATELY SEALED. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.

DURING TRANSPORTATION, MINUTE QUANTITIES VENTED ON TO THE WOODEN PALLETS AND SHRINK WRAP. ENOUGH SEEPED TO CAUSE ODORS. THE PALLETS HAVE BEEN NEUTRALIZED ACCORDING TO CHEMTREC INSTRUCTIONS WITH A BAKING SODA SLURRY. THE NORMAL RIDE OF THE TRAILER APPARENTLY CAUSED ONE OR MORE OF THE THE BARRELS TO VENT AN UNDETERMINED PORTION OF THE ACID. THE FREIGHT WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE WITH NO EXCEPTION.

column168: OUR DRIVER SPOTTED HIS TRAILER FOR LOADINGA AT THE SHIPPER LOCATION.  THE ENTIRE LOADING PROCES IS HANDLED BY THE SHIPPER.  AS PART OF THE LOADING PROCESS THE SHIPPER CHECKS THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND THE INTERNAL VALVE FOR PROPER OPERATION. THE LOADER EVIDENTLY FAILED TO ASSURE HIMSELF THAT THE INTERNAL VALVES WERE PROPERLY CLOSED AND STARTED LOADING. THE EXTERNAL VALVE IS LEFT OPEN AS A MATTER OF COURSE.  SINCE HE DID NOT ASSURE HIMSELF THAT THE INTERNAL WAS CLOSED PRODUCT RAN THROUGH THE TRAILER AND OUT ONTO THE GROUND. THE LOADER WAS DOING PAPER WORK AND FAILED TO NOTICE THE PROBLEM IMMEDIATELY. WHEN HE DID HE CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE AND STOPPED THE LOSS.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE SHIPPER.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT THE CUSTOMERS YARD INTO AN UNDERGROUND TANK. HE WAS ALMOST THROUGH UNLOADING WHEN HE SAW GASOLINE ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE YARD. PRESSURE HAD BUILT UP IN THE TANK FORCING THE FUEL OUT THE REMOTE FILL PIPE.  ALSO THERE WAS SNOW COVERING THIS PIPE.  THE ENGLEWOOD FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND TOOK CHARGE OF THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS.

PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING CAUSING THE CLOSURE TO BREAK RESULTING IN THE LEAKAGE. AREA WAS CLEANED UP AND PLASTIC JUG DISPOSED.

column168: 1-23-90 AT 0923 LOAD ARRIVED AT CARRIER'S FACILITY.  A PUNCTURE IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND AN ODOR WAS NOTED COMING FROM THAT HOLE.  THE UNIT WAS ISOLATED AT CARRIER FACILITY AND VENTED.  CARRIER NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING BY TELEPHONE:  CHEMTREK, AUTHORITIES, SHIPPER, RECEIVER. CHEMTREK ADVISED THAT LOCAL FIRE DEPT RESPONSE TEAMS BE NOTIFIED AND THIS WAS DONE BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. ON SCENE AUTHORITIES ALSO NOTIFIED STATE AND LOCAL E O S AND EPA OFFICES.  A SPEVCIALIST FROM THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY ADVISED THAT HE WOULD BE FLYING TO LITTLE ROCK TO ASSIST AND WOULD ARRIVE AT 1700.  AT 1300 AUTHORITIES SUSPENDED CARRIER OPERATION UNTIL THE MATTER WAS RESOLVED.  AT 1700 SPECIALIST ARRIVED AND BEGAN PREPARATIONS TO ENTER THE TRAILER.  UPON ENTERING THE TRAILER, OFFICIALS DETERMINED THAT SEVERAL SAFETY VALVES ON THE CO CYLINDERS WERE LEAKING AND WOULD HAVE TO BE BLED  DOWN AND COULD BE DONE WITHOUT THREAT TO THE PUBLIC OR ENVIRONMENT. A TOTAL OF 9 CYLINDERS WERE BLED DOWN AND THE SITUATION WAS DETERMINED UNDER CONTROL AND NONTHREATENING.  AT 2130 THE CARRIER WAS ALLOWED TO RESUME NORMAL OPERATIONS.

column168: ON JAN. 10, 1990 THE ASHLAND DRIVER HAD PULLED OVER FOR A TIRE INSPECTION. UPON WALKING AROUND THE TRAILER HE NOTICED ACID DRIPPING FROM THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER SLOWLY OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO IDENTIFY THE LEAKING DRUM. AT OR AROUND THIS SAME TIME THE KANSAS HIGHWAY PATROL HAD ARRIVED. THE PATROLMAN ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND ASKED THE DRIVER IF HE HAD ANY WAY TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND IF HE HAD ANY INFORMATION ON THE PRODUCT. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER GAVE THE PATROLMAN ASHLAND'S 1-800-ASHLAND EMERGENCY NUMBER. THE PATROLMAN WAS PUT IN CONTACT WITH THE EMERGENCY CONTACT AND FAXED THE MSDS FOR THE MATERIAL. THE ASHLAND EMERGENCY CONTACT ALSO CONTACTED THE KANSAS CITY PLANT AND COORDINATED COMMUNICATION OF ALL PARTIES ALONG WITH NOTIFING THE MILLER RURAL FIRE DEPT. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN THE O.K. TO MOVE THE DRUM FROM THE PALLET, TURN IT UPSIDE DOWN AND PLACE IT IN HIS OVERPACK DRUM. THE DRIVER DID THIS AND ALSO SWEPT UP THE CONTAINMENT MATERIAL CONSISTING OF SODA ASH (FOR NEUTRILIZATION OF ACID), AND FLOOR ABSORBANT. THE FIRE DEPT. THEN WASHED AWAY THE RESIDUE. THE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL FROM THE PALLET IT WAS LOADED ON.

THE MATERIAL, DUJET LIQUID STEAM CLEANER, IS A MILD CORROSIVE INDUSTRIAL CLEANING AGENT AND WAS CONTAINERIZED IN TWO 330 GAL BULK TOTES. ON SATURDAY, JANUARY 20, 1990 CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED TO THE RELEASE OF THIS PRODUCT FROM ONE OF THE MENTIONED TOTES. INITIAL CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED AND AT THE REQUEST OF APA AND APPROVAL OF THE DEP THE BOX TRAILER CARRYING THE TOTES HAD BEEN SENT BACK TO THE APA WAREHOUSE WHERE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS WOULD RESUME ON MONDAY.     UPON ARRIVAL AT THE WAREHOUSE, THE APA REPRESENTATIVE REQUESTED THAT CLEAN HARBORS REMOVE ANY REMAINING CONTAMINATED DEBRIS FROM THE TRAILER AND SEGREGATE FOR INVENTORY AND DAMAGE LIABILITY REASONS. MATERIALS WERE REMOVED AND SEGREGATED INTO 3 SEPARATE PILES; ONE CONSISTING OF PAPER PRODUCTS, FOOD STUFFS, AND MEDICAL SUPPLIES; THE SECOND BEING METAL OBJECTS, THE THIRD BEING CHEMICAL CONTAINERS. IT WAS SUGGESTED BY CLEAN HARBORS THAT ANY FOOD STUFFS AND MEDICAL SUPPLIES BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF TO AVOID ANY FUTURE PROBLEMS. ALSO FOR DISPOSAL WOULD BE CONTAMINATED PAPER PRODUCTS AND ANY CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD CONTAINERS. IT WAS ALSO RECOMMENDED THAT ANY METAL OBJECTS BE SEPARATED AND CLEANED WITH A WATER FLUSH AND A DRY WIPING. BECAUSE OF THE POTENTIAL TIME THAT WOULD BE INVOLVED FOR INVENTORY REASONS, THE CLIENT ASSUMED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CONTAINERIZING OF ANY CONTAMINATED MATERIALS AND CLEANING OF METAL MATERIALS.     UPON THE REMOVAL OF THE TOTE TANKS FROM THE TRAILER, A VISUAL INSPECTION WAS PERFORMED ON BOTH TOTES FOR ANY APPARENT DAMAGE. FIRST THE EMPTY TOTE WAS REMOVED. NO APPARENT PHYSICAL DAMAGE WAS PRESENT, THOUGH ON THE UNDER SIDE OF THE TOTE A CHECK VALVE WAS TURNED OPEN AND THE EVERTITE CAP WAS NOT PROPERLY PLACED ON. ONE EAR OF THE CAP HAD BEEN CLOSED BUT THE OTHER WAS OPEN. SO THE CAP WAS NOT COMPLETELY ON, WHICH MAY HAVE RELEASED THE PRODUCT FROM THE 2" MALE DISCHARGE LINE. THE SECOND TOTE WAS ALSO EXAMINED AND FOUND TO BE IN SOUND SHAPE. THE CONTAINER WAS FULL, THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, AND THE CAP PROPERLY PLACED.

ON 1-15-90 WE DISCOVERED 4 DRUMS LAYING ON THEIR SIDE IN TLR. 48-702. SOME OF THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED IN THE TLR. AND HAD CAUSED AN OBNOXIOUS ODOR. AFTER LETTING THE TLR. AIR OUT 2 MEN EQUIPPED WITH RUBBER GLOVES AND MASKS ENTERED THE TLR. AND UPRIGHTED THE DRUMS. SINCE THE DRUMS WERE LABELED CORROSIVE WE CALLED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DIV. OF THE ARIZONA D.O.T. THEY SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO ADVISE US OF THE HANDLING AND HE REFERRED THE SITUATION TO THE CITY OF PHOENIX FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE OFFICERS IN CHARGE DETERMINED THE NATURE OF THE SPILL COULD BE HANDLED BY US IF WE USED PROTECTIVE CLOTHING. ALL THE DRUMS IN QUESTION WERE PUT IN RECOVERY DRUMS AND RETURNED TO ARDROX. ON INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE FIRE DEPT. WE HAD TLR. 48- 702 WASHED OUT BY METRO MOBILE SERVICES BEFORE IT WAS USED AGAIN. A LOCAL DRIVER JOHN YETSICK WHO HAD ENTERED THE TRAILER WITHOUT PROTECTIVE GEAR COMPLAINED OF A HEADACHE AND WAS SENT TO OFFICE MEDICAL CENTER WHERE HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK.

A LOCAL DRIVER JOHN YETSICK WHO HAD ENTERED THE TRAILER WITHOUT PROTECTIVE GEAR COMPLAINED OF A HEADACHE AND WAS SENT TO OFFICE MEDICAL CENTER WHERE HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK.

column168: ON JANUARY 15, 1990, AT 7:15 A.M., ENVIRITE'S DRIVER EXPERIENCED A DISCHARGE OF APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF THE ABOVE-REFERENCED WASTE MATERIAL ONTO PAVEMENT AT THE GENERATOR'S SITE DURING A ROUTINE PICK-UP. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE TRAILER'S VACUUM LOADING SYSTEM AND UTILIZED HYDRATED LIME TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE DRIVER THEN REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE CANTON ENVIRITE FACILITY. ENVIRITE PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED WITH ADDITIONAL LIME, BUCKETS, SHOVELS, AND ABSORBENT PILLOWS. THE MIXTURE OF SPILLED MATERIAL AND LIME WAS SHOVELED UP INTO THE BUCKETS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE ENVIRITE FACILTIY FOR TREATMENT.     THIS INCIDENT WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY EXCESSIVE FOAMING OF THE WASTE DURING A ROUTINE VACUUM LOADING OPERATION. FOAM IS GENERATED BY THE PRESENCE OF SURFACTANTS AND/OR DISPERSANTS IN THE WASTE, FROTHING ACTION CAUSED BY AIR ENTRAINED IN THE WASTE DURING LOADING, AND REDUCED AIR PRESSURE (VACUUM) INSIDE THE VESSEL.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 P.M. MOUNTAIN STANDARD TIME ON JANUARY 14, 1990 A SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA CHEMICAL TRACTOR/BULK TANKER COMBINATION OVERTURNED WHILE NORTHBOUND INTO LOGAN, UTAH ON STATE ROUTE 89/91. THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE WAS THE "BIG CURVE" AREA IN THE SARDINE CANYON NEAR WELLSVILLE, UTAH. THE TANKER WAS CARRYING AN RQ ALKALINE LIQUID, N.O.S. KNOWN BY THE TRADEMARK MACDERMID ULTRA ETCH 20 MANUFACTURED BY SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA CHEMICAL. AN AIR VALVE LOCATED ON THE REAR OF THE TANKER BROKE OFF DURING THE OVERTURN AND A PORTION OF THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED. THE SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA CHEMICAL DRIVER RECEIVED ONLY MINOR INJURIES WHEN THE TRUCK OVERTURNED. THE WELLSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT STOPPED THE LEAK WITHIN 15-30 MINUTES AFTER THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED BY PUTTING A WOOD PLUG INTO THE BROKEN PIPE AND ALSO CONSTRUCTED A SMALL DIKE APPROXIMATELY 40-50 YARDS DOWNGRADE FROM THE TRUCK TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. JACK B KELLEY CO OF WOODS CROSS, UTAH, PERFORMED THE ACTUAL SPILL CLEAN-UP AND PRODUCT TRANSFER.  THE PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED BY EMPLOYEES OF THE JACK B. KELLEY CO. AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 P.M. ON JANUARY 15TH. THE JACK B. KELLEY TANKER WHICH CONTAINED THE RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS DRIVEN TO WOODS CROSS, UTAH FOR FURTHER EVALUATION.     THE SPILLED MATERIAL WHICH WAS CONTAINED BY THE TEMPORARY DIKES CONSTRUCTED BY THE WELLSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE UDOT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY NEUTRALIZED BY MR. LEE NIX OF THE JACK B. KELLEY CO. AS OBSERVED BY LT. AMES OF LTHE UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL. ALSO ATTACHED IS A COPY OF THE UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORT.    SINCE THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF THE SPILLAGE WAS AN AIR VALVE WHICH BROKE OFF, SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA CHEMICAL IS REPLACING ALL THE VALVES WITH A MUCH STURDIER VALVE. IN ADDITION, ALL SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA CHEMICAL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REINSTRUCTED ON DRIVING IN INCLEMENT WEATHER CONDITIONS.
CHERI LEE WAS NOTIFIED OF PROBLEM OF THE STITCHING IN BAGS. 15-20 PELLETS FOUD ABOVE STITCHING OF BAG. SPECIAL AGENT DENNIS M. MCGEE TOOK PHOTOS OF BAGS ON THE TRAILER.

column168: AFTER FUELING, DRIVER WAS INSPECTING UNIT AND NOTICED A SMALL DRIP UNDER 3 OF 8 FLOW BINS BEING TRANSPORTED. THE SHIPPER, MOBIL OIL IN JOLIET, IL, WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE HATCH DOORS ON THE BOTTOM OF THE SHIPPING CONTAINERS (FLOW BINS) HAD WORKED LOOSE AND WAS ALLOWING MATERIAL TO ESCAPE. THE DOORS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE BOTTOM OF THE BIN WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC. THE SHIPMENT WAS SENT BACK TO MOBIL OIL IN JOLIET, IL FOR FURTHER EXAMINATION TO DETERMINE EXACTLY WHAT FAILED. IT WAS THEN LEARNED THAT THE BINS WERE LOADED INSIDE AND THEN STORED OUTSIDE TO COOL WITH NO LIDS ON THE TOPS. DURING THE STORAGE PERIOD OUTSIDE WHICH LASTED SEVERAL DAYS IT SNOWED. WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED SOUT INTO A WARMER CLIMATE, THE SNOW MELTED CAUSING WATER TO MOVE DOWN THROUGH THE CATALYST AND DRIP THROUGH THE HATCH DOORS ON THE BOTTOM. MOBIL OIL HAS ADVISED THAT THEIR LOADING PRACTICES HAVE CHANGED IN THAT BINS WILL NOT BE STORED OUTSIDE WITH LIDS REMOVED. EACH BIN WILL ALSO BE LINED WITH VISQUEEN BEFORE LOADING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TANK TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WEST ON ROUTE 5 WHEN THE RIGHT REAR TIRES DROPPED OFF THE ROAD IN A TURN ONTO THE BERM. THE BERM WAS SOFT AND PULLED THE TRUCK INTO THE DITCH. WHILE TRAVELLING ALONG THE DITCH THE TRUCK HIT A CEMENT CULVERT WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO COME BACK ONTO THE ROAD, TURN SIDEWAYS AND OVERTURN.

VEHICLE WAS PROCEEDING SOUTH ON ROUTE 88 ONLY A FEW MILES FROM SHIPPER WHEN THE DRIVER HEARD AND FELT EXPLOSION WHICH RIPPED THE ROOF OFF THE VAN. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED AS FAR OFF THE ROAD AS PRACTICAL AND DISCOVERED A FIRE IN THE CARGO SECTION OF THE STRAIGHT-TRUCK VAN. A NEARBY RESIDENT NOTIFIED EMERGENCY AGENCIES IMMEDIATELY. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, DUE TO THE "DANGEROUS WHEN WET" NATURE OF THE MATERIAL ALLOWED THE FIRE TO BURN DOWN WHILE USING WATER ONLY TO COOL THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINERS AND THE VEHICLE'S FUEL TANKS. SHIPPER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE SHORTLY AFTER THE INCIDENT AND USED SPECIALIZED FIRE SUPPRESSANT MATERIALS TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE IN ITS LATTER STAGES. SEVEN ORIGINAL DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER USING A SECOND TRANSPORTER. ONE DRUM OF DEBRIS FROM VEHICLE (ASSUMED TO BE HAZARDOUS) WAS ALSO RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS WELL AS 19 DRUMS OF NON-HAZARDOUS RUN-OFF  CLEAN UP MATERIALS. MARCOR CORP PERFORMED CLEAN-UP SERVICES UNDER THE AUSPICES OF THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF CONSERVATION. THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO OUR KENMORE, NY TERMINAL FOR CLEANING. IT IS BELIEVED THAT AN INCENTIVE SPARK IN ONE (1) DRUM CAUSED IGNITION OF THE LITHIUM METAL AND THE HEAT FROM THIS FIRST DRUM IGNITED THE OTHER SIX (6) CONTAINERS. INTERNAL PRESSURE BURST THE TOPS OFF THE DRUMS. THE DRUMS MAINTAINED THEIR INTEGRITY AND ANY LOSS OF MATERIAL WAS DUE TO SMOKE, VAPOR OR THE EXPLOSION.

DRIVER LEFT LAST PICK UP WITH THE DOOR CLOSED, APPARENTLY SAFETY LATCH WAS NOT SECURE. THE DOOR CAME OPEN WHILE ENROUTE AND THE DRUM FELL OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, AND INTO THE INTERSECTION. IT BROKE OPEN THE TOP AND APPROXIMATELY 30% OF THE CONTENTS WERE SPILLED. FIRE AND POLCE WERE IMMEDIATELY ON THE SCENE. CLEAN-UP WAS PERFORMED BY SAMSEL SERVICES COMPANY

WHILE ATTEMPTING TO PUMP OVER WASTE FROM A PORTABLE TANK TO A TANK TRUCK FOR SHIPMENT, VENDOR PERSONNEL LOADING THE MATERIAL FOR THE SHIPPERS LOOSENED A HOSE ON THE TRANSFER PUMP DISCHARGE TO DETERMINE WHY THE PUMP WAS NOT PUMPING. THE PUMP WAS APPARENTLY AIR BOUND AND WHEN THE HOSE WAS LOOSENED, SOME LIQUID (2 GALLONS) SPURTED FROM THE HOSE ONTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT ON WHICH THE PORTABLE TANK AND PUMP WERE LOCATED. ALL OF THE LIQUID, INCLUDING SOME STANDING RAINWATER FROM THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT, WAS VACUUMED UP AND DRUMMED FOR SUBSEQUENT DISPOSAL AFTER HAZARDOUS WASTE ANALYSES ARE COMPLETE. THE VENDOR PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN ASKED TO HANDLE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PER THE SHIPPER'S METHODS IN THE FUTURE. THESE METHODS INCLUDE USING A BUCKET OR OTHER CONTAINER TO CONTAIN ALL PREDICTABLE FLOWS FROM HOSES AND TO TAKE ALL NECESSARY PRECAUTIONS TO PREVENT SPILLS OF ANY LIQUID, ESPECIALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES AND HAZARDOUS WASTES.  THE SHIPMENT WAS CANCELLED DUE TO CIRCUMSTANCES UNRELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

OUR DRIVER HAD STARTED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AT DESTINATION WHEN HE NOTED A SLIGHT LEAK AT THE POINT WHERE THE HOSE IS BANDED TO THE HOSE END. HE SHUT DOWN AND ADVISED THE RECEIVER THAT HE WAS GOING TO HAVE TO CHANGE HOSE. HE SHUT ALL VALVES AND WAS SLOWLY BLEEDING THE PRESSURE FROM THE HOSE BEFORE DISCONNECTING. THE UNLOADER TOLD THE DRIVER THAT HE WOULD DISCONNECT SINCE HE HAD DONE IT A NUMBER OF TIMES BEFORE. HE DISCONNECTED TOO QUICKLY AND PRESSURE IN THE HOSE CAUSED THE MATERIAL TO SPLASH ON HIM. HE WAS NOT WEARING ANY PROTECTIVE CLOTHING EXCEPT FOR SAFETY GLASSES. HE WAS TAKEN TO THE PLANT DISPENSARY, CLEANED UP AND TREATED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A DIKED AREA AND WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER. OUR DRIVER REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE HOSE AND COMPLETED DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

column168: A PACKAGE WAS ABOUT TO BE LOADED INTO A TRAILER ON THE EAST WALL (PURPLE) WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THAT IS WAS LEAKING.  MANAGER JOHN PODERGOIS THEN CALLED THE TOWER TO CONTACT THE RE-WRAP SUPERVISOR.  RE-WRAP CLERK KELLEY RUDE PICKED UP THE PACKAGE IN A SPILL TRAY AND DELIVERED IT TO THE DAMAGE PROCESSING CENTER.  VICKI SCHAAF ALONG WITH LAURIE ANDERSON PROCEEDED TO PROCESS THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS IDENTIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS PACKAGE BY THE CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL AND FIVE PART FORM.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE IT WAS NOTED THE COVER WAS LOOSE ON THE GALLON CONTIANER.  THE PACKAGE WAS RE-WRAPPED ACCORDING TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPING GUIDE AND THE WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE TO THE DISPOSAL PROCEDURES AFTER BEING NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARONATE AND ABOSRBED WITH CHEMSORB.  IT IS STRONGLY RECOMMENDED THAT A CUSTOMER SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE PAY A PERSONAL VISIT TO THE SHIPPER TO DISCUSS THE USEAGE OF PROPER CLOSURES.  NO OTHER BOXES WERE SOILED BY THIS DAMAGE.

column168: NICHOLS FUEL TRUCK WAS MAKING REGULARLY SCHEDULED FUELING RUN TO COSMAR CHEMICAL IN CARVILLE, LA.  AS TRUCK WAS APPROACHING THE GATE TOT HE PLANT IN HEAVY FOG, A CAR CAME AROUND A CURVE IN THE HIGHWAY ON THE WRONG SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY.  THIS FORCED THE FUEL TRUCK INTO THE DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE TRUCK TURNED UP ON ITS RIGHT SIDE, CAUSING THE LOAD OF FUEL TO SHIFT TO THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK.  THE CHANGE IN INTERNAL PRESSURE AGAINST THE TOP LOADING FITTINGS CAUSED TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF DIESEL AND 10 GALLONS OF GASOLINE INTO THE DITCH.  THIS INCIDENT WAS IVESTIGATED BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECTION AND THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP BY THEM.  THE TRUCK SUSTAINED MINOR DAMAGE AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

column168: TANK CAR DUPX 17213, LOAD NITRIC ACID (OVER 40%), WAS RECEIVED AT OUR YOUNGSTOWN, OHIO YARD IN INTERCHANGE FROM CONRAIL, JANUARY 4, 1990 AT 1420 HOURS.  UPON ROUTINE INTERCHANGE FREIGHT CAR INSPECTION, THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT INSPECTOR NOTICED AN ODOR BEING EMITTED FROM THE CAR. BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES DISTRICT INSPECTOR MR. TIM MANNAS WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE. SINCE THE CAR DID NOT APPEAR TO BE CONTINUOUSLY FUMING, IT WAS LOCATE IN AN ISOLATED AREA, NOT NEAR ANY WATERWAYS OR SEWERS AND WE COULD KEEP PEOPLE AWAY WE DECIDED TO WAIT UNTIL DAYLIGHT TO CLOSELY EXAMINE THE CAR FOR A PROBLEM. AT O800 FRIDAY, JANUARY 5, 1990, B OF E INSPECTOR MANNAS AND MYSELF INSPECTED CAR AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING; THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED ALLOWING A LIQUID LEAK AT THIS FITTING. ONE OF FOUR SECUREMENT BOLTS FOR THE LIQUID LINE VALVE BLIND CLOSURE FLANGE DID NOT FULLY ENGAGE ITS NUT. (THREE THREADS OF NUT WERE VISIBLE.)  ON WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 10, 1990 DUPX 17213 WAS PLACED IN WELLAND CHEMICAL PLANT FOR UNLOADING. PRIOR TO THIS MR. MANNAS CONTACTED PERSONNEL AT THE PLANT TO INFORM THEM OF THE NEED TO THOROUGHLY INSPECT VALVE ASSEMBLY AND GASKETS FOR ANY PROBLEMS. ON FRIDAY, JANUARY 12, 1990 MR. MANNAS AND MYSELF WENT TO THE PLANT TO FIND OUT THE RESULTS OF THEIR INSPECTION. NOTHING UNUSUAL OR IRREGULAR WAS NOTED WITH CAR.  WELLAND CHEMICAL CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, DU PONT, AND MADE THEM AWARE OF THE SITUATION. B OF E INSPECTOR MANNAS WILL ALSO FOLLOW UP WITH THE B OF E INSPECTOR RESPONSIBLE FOR THE NEW JERSEY AREA WHERE THE CAR ORIGINATED.

DRIVERS ARE BEING ADVISED TO BE MORE CAREFUL IN POSITIONING THEIR VEHICLES ON CURVES AND RAMPS EVEN WHEN THEY ARE DRIVING AT OR BELOW POSTED SPEEDS.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC ON 1-8-90 - REPORT 00531.

AT APPROXIMATELY 8 A.M. OUR DRIVER, DAVID CARTER, DISCOVERED THAT HE HAD A LEAKING CONTAINER ON THE TRUCK. THIS HE FOUND WHILE DOING A ROUTINE WALK-AROUND INSPECTION PRIOR TO CONTINUING HIS TRIP TO MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS, INC., MORGAN CITY, LA, A FEDERALLY LICENSED TREATMENT FACILITY. MR CARTER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED LOCAL OFFICIALS, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND HIS HOME OFFICE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 8:35 A.M. THEY CALLED ON THE SERVICES OF THE MARYLAND HAZARDOUS INCIDENCE RESPONSE TEAM WHO WERE THE PEPLE TO EVENTUALLY ENTER THE TRAILER AND RETRIEVED THE LEAKING CONTAINER (A FIVE-GALLON CONTAINER). THE CONTAINER HELD WASTE FORMIC ACID SOLUTION. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER, THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE AREA AROUND THE TRAILER, THE MARYLAND TEAM FOUND THE FOLLOWING: APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS LEFT IN THE CONTAINER; APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS ON THE FLOOR OFL KTHE TRAILER; APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON RELEASED ON TO THE GROUND.    FORMIC ACID IS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL WITH AND I.D. NUMBER UN1779 AND AN RQ OF 5000 LBS. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PUT INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM WHICH WE PROVIDED. ADDITIONAL FIVE GALLON CONTAINERS WHICH HAD MATERIAL ON THE TOP AS A RESULT OF THE LEAK WERE ALSO PUT INTO THE OVERPACK DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS DECLARED SAFE FOR TRAVEL AND WAS RELEASED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:45 P.M. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND TRANSPORTED TO MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS, INC.

HOGAN AND SERGEANT JESSE THERIOT OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, DETECTED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM THE SAFETY VENT ON TANK CAR GATX 11201. A CLOSER INSPECTION BY ROBINSON REVEALED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD FAILED. ROBINSON REPLACED THE FAILED DISC WITH A NEW ONE AND RELEASED THE CAR AT 1035 HOURS.  IN ADDITION TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, ROBINSON NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER BY UTILIZING CHEMTREC.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: NOTIFICATION RECEIVED FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, V.H. JOHNSTON, ADVISING TANK CAR UTLX 76995 WAS NOTED LEAKING AT PINE BLUFF, ARKANSAS YARD. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, C.L. HILL, RESPONDED AT 1236 HOURS, SAME DATE, AND HIS INSPECTION REVEALED TWO MANWAY COVER BOLTS OFF MANWAY COVER, THE REMAINING FOUR BOLTS WERE LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT. GASKET WAS INSPECTED, MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURED WRENCH TIGHT.   SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HILL CONTACTED UNION CARBIDE REPRESENTATIVE, O.K. MCCALLISTER, WHO WAS INFORMED OF VIOLATIONS AND RESULT OF IMPROPERLY SECURED TANK CAR. MR. MCCALLISTER ADVISED THIS MATTER WOULD BE HANDLED IMMEDIATELY.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: TRAIN CREW ON NLH026 NOTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE THIRD HEAD CAR DUPX 25001. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C.L. HILL WAS CONTACTED, HIS INSPECTION REVEALED VAPORS COMING FROM B-LIQUID LINE VALVE, FOUND VALVE PLUG LOOSE, TIGHTENED PLUG WHICH STOPPED LEAK. HILL HAD CAR SET OUT OF TRAIN IN AN ISOLATED AREA FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.   AT 1245 HOURS, SAME DATE, DUPONT EMERGENCY RESPONDERS JOE MOORMAN AND WAYNE CHEATAM MADE THEIR INSPECTION, THEY ADVISED THERE WAS NO LEAK, FURTHER THAT CAR COULD BE SENT TO THEIR SHOPS FOR INSPECTION OF B-LIQUID LINE VALVE

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, T M ROBINSON, WAS NOTIFIED BY THE CONDUCTOR THAT THE TANK CAR HAD A SLIGHT LEAK. THE SHIPPER, TRIAD CHEMICAL, HAD BEEN CALLED AND WAS RESPONDING PERSONNEL FROM THE PLANT, TWO MILES FROM THE SCENE. ROBINSON CALLED TRIAD AND SPOKE WITH MR. TOM JOHNSON WHO ADVISED MR. BOB MCKEE AND MR. STEVE MISTRETTA WERE EN ROUTE TO THE SCENE TO CORRECT THE LEAK. ROBINSON NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE OF THE INCIDENT.       AT 1835 HOURS, ROBINSON RECEIVED A CALL FROM TRIAD CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVE BOB MCKEE AT THE SCENE. MCKEE ADVISED THAT THE LEAK WAS A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM THE THERMOMETER WELL. AN ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE THERMONMETER WELL CAP MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS. MCKEE ADVISED THAT THE CAR SHOULD BE MOVED BACK TO TRIAD AS SOON AS POSSIBLE FOR UNLOADING AS NO FURTHER REPAIR COULD BE ATTEMPTED UNDER LOAD.     ROBINSON ARRIVED ON SCENE AT ABOUT 1920 HOURS AND CONTACTED MCKEE AND THEN INSPECTED THE TANK CAR. THIS INSPECTION CONFIRMED MCKEE'S ASSESSMENT OF THE PROBLEM AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO RETURN THE CAR TO THE PLANT FOR UNLOADING.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 NOON, JANUARY 25, 1990, FRA INSPECTORS WORKING IN THE BELEN, NEW MEXICO YARD, DETECTED MINOR LEAKAGE FROM TANK CAR PTLX 223520. THE LEAKAGE OCCURED ONLY WHEN THE RAIL CAR WAS MOVED BECAUSE OF A BAD FIT ON THE DOME COVER. THIS WAS DUE TO A BAD RUBBER GASKET WHICH NEEDED TO BE REPLACED. SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL ISOLATED THE LOAD TO TRACK 7407 UNTIL A REPLACEMENT GASKET COULD BE SHIPPED TO BELEN. ASSISTANT SUPERINTENDENT - EQUIPMENT D.L. WILLIAMS REPLACED THE GASKET AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT ON FEBRUARY 5, 1990.

DURING THE COURSE OF AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA DELIVERY INTO A CUSTOMER'S REFRIGERATION SYSTEM, A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON THE REFRIGERATION SYSTEM FAILED, WHICH CAUSED A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 200 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. THIS AMMONIA RAPIDLY VAPORIZED AND DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.      THE MC330 CARGO TANK DID NOT FAIL AND WAS NOT THE DIRECT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE. A FAULTY PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON THE CUSTOMERS REFRIGERATION SYSTEM WAS DIRECTLY RESPONSIBLE FOR THE RELEASE.     THIS RELEASE WAS REPORTED BY TELEPHONE TO DAVID BENSON AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON 1-5-90 AND ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER 352.

MR. MARSHALL WAS SUMMONED TO THE DOCK TO INSPECT WHAT THE EMPLOYEES THOUGHT WAS A LEAK FROM A OVERHEAD GAS HEATER. THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS THEN DISCOVERED.  MR. MARSHALL PLACED THE BOX IN A PLASTIC BAG AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO DELIVER IT TO THE RECEIVER. UPON RECEIPT AT THE RESEARCH LAB, IT WAS OPENED AND EMITTED A CLOUD OF GAS. THE BOX WAS PUT IN AN EXHAUST HOOD AND THE LAB WAS EVACUATED FOR SEVERAL HOURS. MR. HOWARD OF GLAXO CALLED AIRBORNE EXPRESS OFFICE AT RDU AND SPOKE WITH BILL BOOTH. MR. BOOTH REFERRED MR. HOWARD TO JIM HUTCHINS WHO MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO OBTAIN A RECOVERY DRUM AND PICK UP THE BOX. THE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO AIRBORNE'S DOCK AND THE SAME NIGHT WAS INSPECTED BY BARRY STEELE AND MOVED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPT. IN WILMINGTON, OHIO WHERE IT IS NOW ON HAND. MR. HOWARD AND BEN TAYLOR OF AIRBORNE HAVE BOTH STATED THAT THE INNER RECEPTACLES WERE NOT PROPERLY PACKED IN ABSORBENT AND CUSHIONBING MATERIALS TO AVOID BREAKAGE.

column62: Overfilled; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: CAR NOTED LEAKING ON TRACK #204, MEAD TRANSFER YARD, LONG BEACH, CA. INSPECTION REVEALED 2 OF THE 8 BOLTS WERE LOOSE ON THE PRIMARY FLANGE PLATE OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE DUE TO INTERNAL PRESSURE BUILD UP. BOLTS WERE SECURED AND THE INTERNAL PRESSURE RELIEVED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Hose; Piping or Fittings
column168: SWITCH CREW NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM BOTTOM OF TANK CAR. INSPECTION DETER MINED THAT FUEL OIL WAS POURING OUT OF 'C' CAP 'A'  END, DUPLEX HEATER COIL SYSTEM. THE HEATER COIL OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER HOOKED UP TO CORRECT TANK, BUT TANK WOULD NOT HOLD DELIVERY. 1/2/90 APPROXIMATELY 10:45 PM - RECEIVED A CALL FRO THE TERMINAL, ANY HARPE R, PART-TIMER ON DUTY, THAT TOM SUTHERLAND, SOHIO TRANSPORT DRIVER, HAD A S PILL OF SUPER UNLEADED GASOLINE AT THE MT VERNON BULK PLANT.  QUANTITY APPR OXIMATELY 200 GALLONS, BUT STICK READINGS INDICATE 2000 GALLONS? CALLED R. DONALDSON TO GET SPILL TRAILER AND BRING URV HARTSOCK WITH HIM FO R CLEAN-UP. I LEFT FRO HOME AND PROCEEDED TO THE BULK PLANT. APPROXIMATELY 11:45 - UPON ARRIVAL, I OBSERVED APPROXIMATELY 25-50 GALLONS OF GASOLINE LYING IN THE NW CORNER OF THE DIKE.  TAPE READINGS SHOWED 26' 6 3/4" IN THE TANK.  I ASKED THE DRIVER WHAT HAPPENED. THE DRIVER HAD LOOKED AT THE WRONG TANK CHART.  HE USED CIRCLEVILLE'S DIESE L SUPREME CHART WHICH IS A 30,000 GALLON CHART. APPROXIMATELY 12:00 MIDNIGHT - CALLED BOB BECKLEY, MARKETING DISTRIBUTOR, T O COME TO THE PLANT TO VERIFY THE BEHINNING TANK READING.  THEY SHOWED 16' 6 3/4" WHICH CONFIRMS THE DRIVER'S BEGINNING READING. THE DRIVER'S BEGINNING STICK READING SHOWED 16' 4" ='S 10,633 GALLONS FROM THE CORRECT CHART.  WITH A MAXIMUM CAPACITY OF 17,251 GALLONS, THE TANK WOU LD ONLY HAVE HELD 6,618 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER HAD ON 8,602 GALLONS.  THEREFO RE, A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 1,984 GALLONS.  ACTUAL SPILL HAS BEEN DETERMIN ED TO BE 1,660 GALLONS. THERE WAS 27 FT. IN THE TANK NO 26' 6 3/4" AS TAPE SHOWED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1130, ON JANUARY 30, 1990, CLEAN VENTURE'S VACUUM TRUCK #106 HAD A SPILL OF AN ESTIMATED 25 GALLONS OF WASTE MIXED SOLVENTS. THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM REXHAM FLEXIBLE PACKAGING TO CYCLE CHEM, INC. FOR DISPOSAL.  WHILE STOPPING FOR A RED TRAFFIC LIGHT ON AMBOY AVENUE, AND ESTIMATED 25 GALLONS WAS RELEASED DUE TO AN OPEN VENT LINE.  UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE RELEASE TO THE DRIVER BY THE WOODBRIDGE POLICE DEPARTMENT, THE VENT LINE WAS IMMEDIATLY CLOSED PREVENTING ANY POSSIBILITY OF FURTHER SPILLAGE.  THE DRIVER THAN PROCEEDED TO CALL CVI'S DISPATCHER AND A CLEAN-UP TECHNICIAN, AND I IMMEDIATELY RESPONSED TO THE SCENE.  THE NJDEP SPILL HOTLINE WAS CALLED AND THE SPILL REPORTED TO DEP OPERATOR #8 AND DEP CASE #90-09-30-1238 AND CROSS REFERENCE CASE #90-01-30-1223 WERE ASSIGNED.  THE SPILL OCCURRED ON AN ASPHALT AND CONCRETE ROADWAY WITH NO MATERIAL ENTERING ANY DRAINS, SEWERS OR WATERWAYS.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE, THE MATERAIL WAS QUICKLY ABSORBED WITH SPEEDY DRY AND THE ROADWAY CLEANED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE MIDDLESEX COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT.  AT 1315 THE SPILL WAS CLEANED TO THE SATISFACTION OF ALL PARTIES.  ONE DRUM OF CONTAMINATED SPEEDY DRY AND PROTECTIVE CLOTHING WAS GENERATED.  THE DRUM WAS BROUGTH TO CLEAN VNETURE'S OFFICE AT 1160 STATE STREET, PERTH AMBOY, NEW JERSEY UNDER THE ESCORT OF THE MIDDLESEEX COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT.  ON FEBRUARY 1, 1990, THE DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED TO CYCLE  CHEM, INC. FOR DISPOSAL ON N.J. MANIFEST NO. NJA0762438.  CLEAN VENTURE, IN.
